<br>
Please allow me to share a tale which happened to … a friend of mine some time back, shortly after the Chalice of Rain from the Temple of Thunder in Qeynos went missing (not that I… not that my <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> friend</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> had anything to do with that, of course).<br>
<br>
At that time my friend was partnered with an Othmir rogue named Otto – quick of wit and quicker of fingers, but unfortunately not so quite so quick of foot.  We… They had stopped in a small village in the Karanas to reprovision and my friend, being better able to move about the town, left Otto hidden outside town while she went shopping.<br>
<br>
My friend was enjoying herself quite a bit.  Open market shopping is hard to be beat, the League of Antonican Bards had a rollicking orchestra, and it was the time of year for the annual elephant drive.  There were plenty of strangers around and the merchants were easily convinced to give her Bristlebane’s discount (or at least if they noticed, there were plenty of others at hand to blame it on).  She was listening to one of the drive-masters explain how he used an ivory whistle to call his elephants to him when they had wandered off, when the first sign of trouble presented itself.  <br>
<br>
The drive-master’s whistle demonstration petered out mid-puff as a parade of paladins clanged by.  Amongst their cheers and shield beating, it was quickly apparent that they had taken Otto captive and were blaming him for the theft in Qeynos (which of course he had had nothing to do with, and even if he had, he hadn’t left any evidence).  <br>
<br>
As I’m sure you know, one doesn’t want to fall into the hands of the Knights of Thunder.  They don’t understand anybody not wanting to follow their ascetic ways, and they burn with a Hatred for anybody different that would do Innoruuk proud.  And Otto was very different from what the Paladins were used to.<br>
<br>
The smart thing at this point would have been for my friend to cut her losses and leave, abandoning Otto to his fate.  Those who say there is no honor amongst thieves (not, of course, that my friend was a thief), would have expected it.  But for whatever reason – whether it was honor, or friendship, or that Otto was the only one who knew where the missing Chalice was now located (not, of course that he and my friend had anything to do with its disappearance) – she couldn’t leave him to the Paladins.<br>
<br>
Pulling her hood around her, my friend slipped into the crowd and sought out where her partner was being held.  <br>
<br>
Hidden with all of the subtlety of a Paladin, he was easy to find.<br>
<br>
A gallows had been set up on the far side of the fair, near where the bards were boisterously oom-pahing along.  Her partner was locked in a building not far away, guarded by several armored knights.  There was no way to spring him from his cell itself before Otto was hanged, but perhaps there was a chance he was carried from his cell to the gallows.<br>
<br>
Haste makes waste, but sometimes one doesn’t have a choice.  A cart and disguises could serve for the getaway, and nobody would notice if one were moved closer to where she planned the rescue.  All that remained was to surprise the guards, rescue her partner, and be off in the confusion.<br>
<br>
Easy, right?<br>
<br>
Right.<br>
<br>
With three people, she could do it, but there were too many guards for her to beat them all herself.  She didn’t know anybody whose aid she could depend on, and there wasn’t nearly enough time to approach the local ring for aid (not, of course, that such a thing existed, nor that she’d know about it if they did).  <br>
<br>
The tidings looked grim for Otto, but without another two it was hopeless.<br>
<br>
My friend surveyed the area one last time before giving up.  The Bards oom-pahed along.  The elephants trumpeted in the background.  The mob rumbled.  The Paladins opened the cell door and began carrying her partner to his doom.<br>
<br>
Dejectedly, she thrust her hands in her pockets, despairing of any rescue; but it was only almost too late.  She carefully pulled the answer to her dilemma from her pocket and scanned the crowd.  The timing would be just right.  <br>
<br>
Putting the drive-master’s whistle to her lips she let loose a high, shrill note.  Thundering hooves trampled the Bardic orchestra and captured the Paladins’ attention while she grabbed her friend and disappeared in the chaos.<br>
<br>
“Yes,” she mused to herself, “a herd in the band is worth two in ambush.”<br>
